{
    "tactics": {
        "title": "Tactics",
        "order": 2.05,
        "description": [
            "A tactic is a sequence of ",
            {
                "type": "wrap_bold",
                "text": "forcing moves"
            },
            ", designed to overwhelm the opponent's ability to defend against them unscathed.",
            " They are typically short, ",
            {
                "type": "glossary_button",
                "text": "calculated",
                "value": "choosing_a_move"
            },
            " combinations aiming to create an immediate concrete advantage or even to force checkmate, in contrast to ",
            {
                "type": "glossary_button",
                "text": "positional chess",
                "value": "positional_chess"
            },
            " which tends to concern more abstract and incremental improvements over a longer period.",
            {
                "type": "highlight_box",
                "header": "Index: Tactical Motifs",
                "value": [
                    {
                        "type": "glossary_button",
                        "text": "X-Ray Attack",
                        "value": "x_ray_attacks"
                    }, " ",
                    {
                        "type": "glossary_button",
                        "text": "Pin",
                        "value": "pins"
                    }, " ",
                    {
                        "type": "glossary_button",
                        "text": "Skewer",
                        "value": "skewers"
                    }, " ",
                    {
                        "type": "glossary_button",
                        "text": "Discovered Attack",
                        "value": "discovered_attacks"
                    }, " ",
                    {
                        "type": "glossary_button",
                        "text": "Multi-Attack",
                        "value": "multi_attacks"
                    }, " ",
                    {
                        "type": "glossary_button",
                        "text": "Fork",
                        "value": "forks"
                    }
                ]
            },
            "Forcing moves can be broadly categorised by degree, as follows:",
            {
                "type": "unordered_list",
                "value": [
                    [
                        {
                            "type": "wrap_bold",
                            "text": "Checks"
                        },
                        " are the most forcing type of move, as they obligate the target to address them in order to",
                        " remove their king from danger."
                    ],
                    [
                        {
                            "type": "wrap_bold",
                            "text": "Captures"
                        },
                        " are less forcing than checks as they ",
                        {
                            "type": "wrap_italic",
                            "text": "can"
                        },
                        " legally be ignored; however, unless there is something of greater importance to focus on in the",
                        " position, ignoring a capture made by the opponent risks acquiring no compensation for it ",
                        {
                            "type": "glossary_button",
                            "text": "material",
                            "value": "material_value",
                            "punctuation": ["(", null]
                        },
                        " or ",
                        {
                            "type": "glossary_button",
                            "text": "otherwise",
                            "value": "imbalances",
                            "punctuation": ")"
                        },
                        " and therefore playing at a subsequent disadvantage."
                    ],
                    [
                        {
                            "type": "wrap_bold",
                            "text": "Threats"
                        },
                        ", or ",
                        {
                            "type": "wrap_bold",
                            "text": "attacks"
                        },
                        " (positioning or otherwise facilitating a piece or pawn to capture an opponent's piece or pawn,",
                        " or more generally aiming to cause the opponent some other problem, on the next turn) are the least",
                        " forcing type of forcing move as they do not actually place the target at a concrete disadvantage",
                        " before the threat is acted upon; it is still typically necessary to address them proactively."
                    ]
                ]
            },
            "These three categories form the backbone of a player's ",
            {
                "type": "wrap_italic",
                "text": "tactical vision"
            },
            ". They are commonly used turn-by-turn to prioritise which possible moves to consider first in a given position,",
            " and likewise to prioritise which of an opponent's possible moves to consider first in order to determine",
            " what they may do next, under the acronym ",
            {
                "type": "wrap_bold",
                "text": "CCT"
            },
            " (Checks, Captures & Threats) or ",
            {
                "type": "wrap_bold",
                "text": "CCA"
            },
            " (Checks, Captures & Attacks).",
            {
                "type": "incomplete"
            }
        ]
    },
    "discovered_attacks": {
        "title": "Discovered Attack",
        "hide": true,
        "order": 2.1,
        "description": [
            "A ",
            {
                "type": "glossary_button",
                "text": "tactical",
                "value": "tactics"
            },
            " motif in which a direct attack by one piece is revealed when another piece or pawn is moved out of its way.",
            {
                "type": "highlight_box",
                "value": [
                    "In this ",
                    {
                        "type": "set_moves_button",
                        "text": "example",
                        "value": ["e4", "e5", "Nf3", "Nf6", "Nxe5", "Nxe4", "Qe2", "Nf6", "Nc6+"]
                    },
                    " from ",
                    {
                        "type": "wrap_italic",
                        "text": "Petrov's Defence"
                    },
                    ", Black has made the blunder ",
                    {
                        "type": "annotated_move",
                        "value": "e4 e5 Nf3 Nf6 Nxe5 Nxe4 Qe2 Nf6",
                        "is_short": true,
                        "punctuation": ","
                    },
                    " allowing White to play the crushing discovered check ",
                    {
                        "type": "annotated_move",
                        "value": "e4 e5 Nf3 Nf6 Nxe5 Nxe4 Qe2 Nf6 Nc6+",
                        "is_short": true
                    },
                    " in response.",
                    "\n\nBy moving the knight out of the way, White's queen now ",
                    {
                        "type": "glossary_button",
                        "text": "sees",
                        "value": "piece_vision"
                    },
                    " Black's king, and White's knight is safe from immediate capture while Black spends their move blocking",
                    " the check. White may then capture Black's queen with the knight on their next move.",
                    "\n\nIn this case, the discovered attack is also a form of ",
                    {
                        "type": "glossary_button",
                        "text": "double attack",
                        "value": "multi_attacks",
                        "punctuation": ","
                    },
                    " as the knight and queen create two separate threats."
                ]
            },
            {
                "type": "incomplete"
            }
        ]
    },
    "choosing_a_move": {
        "created": "2026-05-27",
        "updated": "2026-06-04",
        "title": "Choosing a Move",
        "order": 2.2,
        "description": [
            "For experienced players, the processes of evaluating a position and finding strong moves are tackled using",
            " a combination of methods:",
            {
                "type": "unordered_list",
                "value": [
                    [
                        {
                            "type": "wrap_bold",
                            "text": "Understanding the "
                        },
                        {
                            "type": "glossary_button",
                            "text": "context",
                            "value": "context"
                        },
                        " of a position is a crucial first step, as this will affect the importance of any subsequent",
                        " reasoning for candidate moves - a move which would win ",
                        {
                            "type": "glossary_button",
                            "text": "material",
                            "value": "material_value"
                        },
                        " on the spot may sound tempting, until the broader context reveals that it would also allow the",
                        " opponent to play checkmate."
                    ],
                    [
                        {
                            "type": "wrap_bold",
                            "text": "Raw calculation"
                        },
                        " is the obvious, and the most reliable, approach; However, due to the exponential",
                        " increase in possible outcomes as a sequence of moves gets longer, it simply isn't feasible to",
                        " apply this method on its own for most positions.",
                        "\nIt is at its most useful when searching for ",
                        {
                            "type": "glossary_button",
                            "text": "tactics",
                            "value": "tactics",
                            "punctuation": ","
                        },
                        " including determining whether there is a forced checkmate available."
                    ],
                    [
                        {
                            "type": "glossary_button",
                            "text": "Positional",
                            "value": "positional_chess"
                        },
                        {
                            "type": "wrap_bold",
                            "text": " principles"
                        },
                        ", which are typically derived from studying common patterns and their usual outcomes,",
                        " form general guidelines to follow where calculation becomes impractical. Because they are not",
                        " absolute rules, each positional principle has exceptions to its application, and weighing the",
                        " benefits of various principles against each other is often more art than science."
                    ],
                    [
                        "When playing against another human, it is possible to consider moves from the perspective of capitalizing",
                        " on human limitations; a move which may not be an optimal choice in a given position can instead be played",
                        " for its ability to ",
                        {
                            "type": "wrap_bold",
                            "text": " bait"
                        },
                        " a bad response, to ",
                        {
                            "type": "wrap_bold",
                            "text": "complicate"
                        },
                        " the position such that it is difficult for a human player to calculate a winning line, or (during",
                        " the opening) with the aim of reaching a position that is not covered by book theory so that the opponent",
                        " cannot play from memory.",
                        "\n\nUnlike the previous methods, this style of play is ",
                        {
                            "type": "wrap_bold",
                            "text": "optional"
                        },
                        " in regard to consistently finding strong moves;",
                        " players at all levels may employ it to varying degrees, or not at all.",
                        {
                            "type": "highlight_box",
                            "value": [
                                {
                                    "type": "wrap_italic",
                                    "text": [
                                        "“You must take your opponent into a deep dark forest where 2+2=5, and the path leading",
                                        " out is only wide enough for one.“"
                                    ]
                                },
                                "\n\n― ",
                                {
                                    "type": "link",
                                    "text": "Mikhail Tal",
                                    "target": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mikhail_Tal"
                                }
                            ]
                        },
                        {
                            "type": "highlight_box",
                            "value": [
                                {
                                    "type": "wrap_italic",
                                    "text": [
                                        "“On the chessboard, lies and hypocrisy do not survive long.”"
                                    ]
                                },
                                "\n\n― ",
                                {
                                    "type": "link",
                                    "text": "Emanuel Lasker",
                                    "target": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Emanuel_Lasker"
                                }
                            ]
                        },
                        "Even with this approach, it is important to avoid moves for which there is a clear winning response, or",
                        " which put the player at an obvious disadvantage without comparable ",
                        {
                            "type": "glossary_button",
                            "text": "compensation",
                            "value": "imbalances"
                        },
                        " - such moves are typically referred to as playing ",
                        {
                            "type": "wrap_bold",
                            "text": "hope chess"
                        },
                        ", and will be punished by stronger players."
                    ]
                ]
            }
        ]
    },
    "control": {
        "title": "Control",
        "order": 2.3,
        "description": [
            "A ",
            {
                "type": "glossary_button",
                "text": "positional",
                "value": "positional_chess"
            },
            " attribute describing the arrangement of a player's pieces or pawns to ",
            {
                "type": "glossary_button",
                "text": "cover",
                "value": "piece_vision"
            },
            " or otherwise block access to key squares, preventing the opponent from placing pieces or pawns on those",
            " squares and/or enabling the player to safely place their own pieces and pawns on those squares.",
            "\n\nTaking control of a square or region specifically to deny it from the opponent is a form of ",
            {
                "type": "glossary_button",
                "text": "prophylaxis",
                "value": "prophylaxis",
                "punctuation": "."
            },
            "\n\nSquares or regions of the board can be controlled ",
            {
                "type": "wrap_italic",
                "text": "directly"
            },
            " (via coverage), or ",
            {
                "type": "wrap_italic",
                "text": "indirectly"
            },
            ":",
            {
                "type": "unordered_list",
                "value": [
                    [
                        "In the ",
                        {
                            "type": "set_moves_button",
                            "text": "King's Indian Defence",
                            "value": ["d4", "Nf6", "c4", "g6", "Nc3", "Bg7"],
                            "punctuation": ","
                        },
                        " Black ",
                        {
                            "type": "glossary_button",
                            "text": "fianchettos",
                            "value": "fianchetto"
                        },
                        " the kingside bishop. This exerts indirect control of the ",
                        {
                            "type": "glossary_button",
                            "text": "centre",
                            "value": "centre"
                        },
                        " - the bishop is",
                        " blocked by the knight, but x-rays e5 and the pawn on d4."
                    ],
                    [
                        "In ",
                        {
                            "type": "set_moves_button",
                            "text": "this",
                            "value": "e4 Nf6 e5 Nd5 d4 d6 Nf3 Bg4 Be2 e6 O-O Be7 c4"
                        },
                        " position from the main line of ",
                        {
                            "type": "wrap_italic",
                            "text": "Alekhine's Defence"
                        },
                        ", Black cannot move the ",
                        {
                            "type": "glossary_button",
                            "text": "hanging",
                            "value": "hanging"
                        },
                        " knight to b4 because White has indirect (or ",
                        {
                            "type": "glossary_button",
                            "text": "tactical",
                            "value": "tactics",
                            "punctuation": ")"
                        },
                        " control of it.",
                        "\n",
                        {
                            "type": "annotated_move",
                            "value": "e4 Nf6 e5 Nd5 d4 d6 Nf3 Bg4 Be2 e6 O-O Be7 c4 Nb4",
                            "is_short": true
                        },
                        " will be met with ",
                        {
                            "type": "annotated_move",
                            "value": "e4 Nf6 e5 Nd5 d4 d6 Nf3 Bg4 Be2 e6 O-O Be7 c4 Nb4 Qa4+",
                            "is_short": true,
                            "punctuation": ","
                        },
                        " ",
                        {
                            "type": "glossary_button",
                            "text": "forking",
                            "value": "forks"
                        },
                        " the knight and king, and if Black blocks the check with either ",
                        {
                            "type": "wrap_bold",
                            "text": "N4c6"
                        },
                        " or ",
                        {
                            "type": "wrap_bold",
                            "text": "N8c6"
                        },
                        " White can then pressure the ",
                        {
                            "type": "glossary_button",
                            "text": "pin",
                            "value": "pins"
                        },
                        " with ",
                        {
                            "type": "annotated_move",
                            "value": "e4 Nf6 e5 Nd5 d4 d6 Nf3 Bg4 Be2 e6 O-O Be7 c4 Nb4 Qa4+ N4c6 d5",
                            "is_short": true
                        },
                        " to win the knight."
                    ],
                    [
                        {
                            "type": "glossary_button",
                            "text": "Space",
                            "value": "space"
                        },
                        " is a form of indirect control."
                    ]
                ]
            }
        ]
    },
    "prophylaxis": {
        "order": 2.4,
        "title": "Prophylaxis",
        "description": [
            "In ",
            {
                "type": "glossary_button",
                "text": "positional chess",
                "value": "positional_chess",
                "punctuation": ","
            },
            " a prophylactic move is a move made by a player to prevent their opponent from carrying out a plan that",
            " the player deems undesirable.",
            "\nThis can take a variety of forms, with some of the most common including ",
            {
                "type": "glossary_button",
                "text": "luft",
                "value": "luft"
            },
            " and ",
            {
                "type": "wrap_bold",
                "text": "area denial"
            },
            " (taking ",
            {
                "type": "glossary_button",
                "text": "control",
                "value": "control"
            },
            " of a square to prevent the opponent from making use of it).",
            {
                "type": "highlight_box",
                "value": [
                    "In the ",
                    {
                        "type": "wrap_italic",
                        "text": "Anti-Fried Liver Defence"
                    },
                    ", Black plays the prophylactic move ",
                    {
                        "type": "set_moves_button",
                        "text": "3. ...h6",
                        "value": ["e4", "e5", "Nf3", "Nc6", "Bc4", "h6"]
                    },
                    " to prevent White from placing their knight on g5, targeting the ",
                    {
                        "type": "glossary_button",
                        "text": "f7 square",
                        "value": "the_f-pawn",
                        "punctuation": "."
                    }
                ]
            }
        ]
    }
}
